      In no wise fairly, or with suffiecient admiration, the Mr. Holland of the NY times, desbribed Kreisler's violin, perhaps Kreisleriana itself,
 as "soupy." As if his sweet melodies could have been strung from a foul rag, as if a nostalgic, centimental, bawling mother, dropping tears 
into her stew, having torn the hairnet from her head in desperation of her abscent husband, could have been responsible, for the godly
contributions that are so uniquely Chrystler.